### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

compiler-cli

### Description

The current documentation for Vitest is quite bad, there isn't even a example but there is a test output.

This could lead to a wrong perception about the technology not being adopted fast enough

see:
- https://angular.dev/guide/testing/unit-tests


A good example is this article:
https://www.angular.courses/new-in-angular/20/

there is a example for a
` expect(true).toBe(true);`


Test, that has nothing to do with angular :)

and for the:
Browser testing support  - The author probably ment - Browser Mode there is no example, probably the author had problems to find a working example for it.



**Acceptance Criteria**

- An example for browser mode and simulated DOM is provider with their configuration


### Proposed solution

An example.

```
import {expect, test} from 'vitest';

import {ComponentFixture, TestBed} from '@angular/core/testing';
import {provideZonelessChangeDetection} from '@angular/core';
import {WelcomeComponent} from './pages/welcome/welcome.component';

/// <reference types="@vitest/browser/providers/playwright" />

describe('UserComponent', () => {
  let component: WelcomeComponent;
  let fixture: ComponentFixture<WelcomeComponent>;

  beforeEach(async () => {
    await TestBed.configureTestingModule({
      imports: [WelcomeComponent],
      providers: [provideZonelessChangeDetection()],
    }).compileComponents();

    fixture = TestBed.createComponent(WelcomeComponent);
    component = fixture.componentInstance;
  });

  test('should update username signal', async () => {
    fixture.detectChanges();

    const compiled = fixture.nativeElement;
    expect(compiled.textContent).toContain('OK');
  });
});

```

### Alternatives considered

The community comes up with it, but seams like the community is struggling :)

Currently, Angular's `httpResource` does not expose the `referrer` and `integrity` options from the underlying Fetch API.

Exposing these options would provide developers with finer control over the request's **referrer** and **subresource integrity validation**, which are important for ensuring **security**, **privacy**, and **trust** in critical resource fetching scenarios.

New Usage Example

```ts
httpResource(() => ({
  url: '${CDN_DOMAIN}/assets/data.json',
  method: 'GET',
  referrer: 'no-referrer',
  integrity: 'sha384-oqVuAfXRKap7fdgcCY5uykM6+R9GhEXAMPLEKEY='
}));

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Hey! 

In the past days, we had an interesting issue in some signals powered code that generated confusion. Here's a snippet demonstrating the problem: 

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  imports: [AsyncPipe],
  template: `
    <h1>toOb - toSign</h1>
    <hr>
    <div>obs$: {{ obs$ | async }}</div>
    <div>newValue: {{ newValue() }}</div>
    <hr>
    <button (click)="updateOther()">other: {{ other() }}</button>
    @if (other() % 2 === 0) {
      <span>{{ other() }} is even</span>
    }
  `,
})
export class App {
  private readonly http = inject(HttpClient);

  protected readonly value = signal(Date.now());
  protected readonly obs$ = toObservable(this.value).pipe(
    switchMap((v) => {
      // Note: just add a catch to fix the issue
      // return this.http.get(`${v}`).pipe(catchError(() => of(v)));

      return this.http.get(`not-caught-http-error-${v}`);
    })
  );
  protected readonly newValue = toSignal(this.obs$);
  protected readonly other = signal(Date.now());

  updateOther() {
    // not working
    this.other.set(Date.now());
  }
}
```
https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-yrzmqbqx?file=src%2Fmain.ts

Some notes: 
- there's no disagreement this is poorly design code (working with the team in charge of the package to refactor the code), 
- `obs$` was more complicated but it essentially fires an http request that can legitimately fail (404) without any catch (I know ðŸ˜…), 
- an `HttpErrorResponse` is logged in the console, but there's no real sign (NG-X error or similar) the reactivity graph is fully affected (from what I was able to see: the entire app was broken). 

The confusion (for myself as well) came from the difficulty of correlating the root cause with the details of the error: 
- 404 status code, 
- `HttpErrorResponse`, 
- broken application. 

So I wonder: do you think it would be possible to better recognise - treat such situations at angular level and provide more meaningful feedback? 

As already mentioned: no disagreement this is bad code... it is just innocently and dangerously problematic! ðŸ˜…

Thanks a lot!  

### Proposed solution

If possible, more scoped feedback for developers

### Alternatives considered

Write better code ðŸ˜‚

